ily changed on both sides. He demonstrates that the United States and Japan became increasingly alike over the course of the war, perhaps most tellingly in their common attempts to disavow racism even as they reproduced it in new ways and forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xParticipation, Japanese American. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszJapan. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zKorea. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095036840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520950368/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles